30:52.417 --> 30:54.119
O'Malley.

30:57.988 --> 31:00.725
Ah, Mr. Bennett
from the Herald.

31:00.758 --> 31:02.827
Come to take in
another show, huh?

31:02.860 --> 31:04.028
Tell me, Mr. Barnum,

31:04.061 --> 31:05.196
does it bother you

31:05.230 --> 31:08.133
that everything
you're selling is fake?

31:08.833 --> 31:10.468
Do these smiles seem fake?

31:10.501 --> 31:11.745
It doesn't matter
where they come from.

31:11.769 --> 31:12.970
The joy is real.

31:13.003 --> 31:14.539
So, you are a philanthropist?

31:14.572 --> 31:17.275
Well, hyperbole
isn't the worst crime.

31:17.308 --> 31:20.278
Men suffer more from imagining
too little than too much.

31:20.311 --> 31:22.747
The creed of a true fraud.

31:24.081 --> 31:26.284
Mr. Bennett, when was
the last time you smiled

31:26.317 --> 31:28.719
or had a good laugh?
Like a real laugh?

31:30.188 --> 31:33.258
A theater critic who can't
find joy in the theater.

31:33.291 --> 31:35.526
Now who's a fraud?

31:37.895 --> 31:40.030
Oh, Mr. Bennett.

31:40.064 --> 31:42.833
That word you used
to describe my show?

31:43.901 --> 31:45.102
Has a nice ring to it.

31:55.180 --> 31:56.914
And right this way.

31:56.947 --> 32:00.117
Don't you think there's enough
blind trust in my life?

32:00.151 --> 32:01.819
Well, isn't that
what makes it fun?

32:01.852 --> 32:05.790
Keep coming. Okay.
Are you ready?

32:12.230 --> 32:13.831
- Is it?
- It is.

32:16.901 --> 32:19.136
Come on. Let's go.

32:19.437 --> 32:20.671
Push.

32:22.807 --> 32:23.808
Wow.

32:25.776 --> 32:27.478
Helen, that's for you.

32:30.215 --> 32:33.818
And Caroline,
this is for you.

32:41.192 --> 32:43.060
There's a ballet school
right down the street.

32:43.093 --> 32:45.663
Just past your
parents' house, actually.

32:47.398 --> 32:48.833
Don't tell me
you bought this house

32:48.866 --> 32:51.202
just to rub my parents' noses
in your success?

32:51.236 --> 32:53.438
Well, that wasn't
the only reason.

32:54.905 --> 32:57.242
This is the life I promised you.

32:57.942 --> 32:59.377
Shall we?

32:59.410 --> 33:02.880
Phin, it's beautiful,

33:02.913 --> 33:04.725
but you know, we don't
need all of this to be...

33:04.749 --> 33:06.183
It only took me 25 years,

33:06.217 --> 33:09.153
but welcome home,
Charity Barnum.

33:47.792 --> 33:49.994
- Hello, there.
- There goes Barnum.

33:57.368 --> 34:00.070
Hey, sweetheart,
who's that young man over there?

34:00.104 --> 34:01.872
Oh, that's Phillip Carlyle.

34:01.906 --> 34:04.309
A bit of a scandal, they say.

34:04.342 --> 34:05.910
His last play
was a hit in London.

34:05.943 --> 34:07.512
Play? You pay good money

34:07.545 --> 34:10.080
to watch people stand around
and talk for two hours

34:10.114 --> 34:11.549
and they call me a con man.

34:11.581 --> 34:14.918
Ew, what's that smell?
Do you smell that?

34:14.952 --> 34:17.154
Ew. Something does smell.

34:17.187 --> 34:20.024
Oh, I know what it is.
Peanuts.

34:29.766 --> 34:31.302
I can see it right now.

34:31.335 --> 34:32.637
"Youngest prima ballerina

34:32.670 --> 34:34.539
in the history
of the City Ballet."

34:36.239 --> 34:37.442
I'm quitting.

34:37.475 --> 34:39.344
What? Why would you quit?

34:39.377 --> 34:41.779
I started too late.
I'll never catch up.

34:41.812 --> 34:43.947
Caroline, you were the best
dancer on that stage.

34:45.583 --> 34:48.319
What? You think
I can't spot talent?

34:48.353 --> 34:50.987
Ballet takes years
of hard work.

34:51.021 --> 34:52.389
It's not like the circus.

34:54.091 --> 34:55.360
You can't just fake it.

34:59.897 --> 35:01.131
She can't quit. No.

35:01.165 --> 35:02.400
No, I mean, she just...

35:02.433 --> 35:04.244
She just feels out of place
with the other girls.

35:04.268 --> 35:05.770
Well, I should
certainly hope so.

35:05.803 --> 35:08.105
I've never seen so many
little prima donnas in my life.

35:08.138 --> 35:10.351
Yeah, but those prima donnas
are the most important thing

35:10.375 --> 35:11.676
in the world to her right now.

35:11.709 --> 35:14.078
She'll learn to ignore them
just like I did.

35:14.111 --> 35:15.513
She shouldn't have to.

35:15.546 --> 35:17.515
New York society
will never accept us.

35:17.548 --> 35:19.350
If they did,
they'd have to stop judging

35:19.384 --> 35:21.218
and actually do something
with their lives.

35:21.251 --> 35:22.620
This isn't about me.

35:23.754 --> 35:28.393
Oh. So it's different
than everything else then?

35:28.426 --> 35:31.061
I just want her to be proud
of who she is, of her family.

35:31.095 --> 35:33.163
She is proud.

35:33.197 --> 35:34.799
We don't have
to be the Carlyles.

35:40.438 --> 35:42.473
Mr. Carlyle.
You produced this play?

35:42.507 --> 35:44.642
Yes, I did indeed.

35:44.675 --> 35:46.877
Refunds are available
at the front box office.

35:46.911 --> 35:48.679
P.T. Barnum.

35:48.713 --> 35:49.614
From the circus?

35:49.647 --> 35:51.616
Yes. You... you've been?

35:51.649 --> 35:55.085
God, no. But I have
seen the crowds.

35:55.119 --> 35:57.731
People leave your shows a great deal
happier than when they came in.

35:57.755 --> 36:00.391
Which is much more
than I can say for my play.

36:00.425 --> 36:02.660
And yet, you have
no trouble selling tickets.

36:04.328 --> 36:06.063
That's because
I'm selling virtue.

36:08.365 --> 36:09.700
Can I buy you a drink?

36:11.769 --> 36:14.071
I wanna go after
the carriage trade.

36:14.104 --> 36:16.173
Present legitimate acts,

36:16.206 --> 36:19.544
expand our appeal,
go after the snobs.

36:19.577 --> 36:21.912
If you only knew
how suffocating they are.

36:21.946 --> 36:23.380
So come join the circus.

36:23.414 --> 36:25.094
You clearly have a flair
for show business.

36:26.551 --> 36:28.385
Teach me how to appeal
to the highbrows.

36:29.454 --> 36:31.589
- Are you serious?
- Mm-hmm.

36:31.622 --> 36:33.991
Mr. Barnum, I can't just run off
and join the circus.

36:34.024 --> 36:35.993
